0.body: Welcome to YOOT's official documentation YOOT is a minimalistic CMS focused on simplicity and ease of use. It aims to provide a quick way for content driven business owners and their developers to spin up storage for their applications. YOOT offers a friendly web interface to manage your data and also an API that exposes that data to external apps. This documentation focuses only on how to use the API. If you want a quick your of the Yoot console , watch this YouTube video .
0.title: INTRODUCTION

1.body: A project in YOOT terms stands for something like a database. The project is created on the console and inside a project are Entities which could be compared to SQL tables, finally these Entities contains entries which can be compared to rows in an SQL database.

14.body: Here is a list of error codes you might get back from YOOT's API and what they mean
14.title: Errors

17.body: Means that a resource has been created

18.body: Invalid or missing API key in request headers

19.body: Missing required permission on API key

2.body: Projects are created on the console, and one or many API keys can be linked to a project. These keys have permissions, set by the project owner. Yoot API keys have 4 main permissions: Read permissions: With this permission, the key is authorized to fetch any data contained in the project. That means any entity and any entry contained in any of these entities. Create permission: With this permission, the key is able to create data in the project. That means the key can be used to create entities and insert entries in any entities. Write permission: Slightly different from the Create permission, this one allows the key to modify existing data in the project. A key with Create permission can create data but not modify that data. A key with only Write permission can modify data but can not create any new data Delete permission: This one's name speaks for itself. With this permission the key is able to delete existing data in the project. Note that the Read permission is always granted by default to the key and can not be removed

23.body: Except for GET requests, every request you sent to the API must have their Content-Type header set to'multipart/form-data'
23.title: ERR_CONTENT_TYPE

24.body: Is returned when the request body does not contain all required keys or does not match the required format
24.title: ERR_BAD_REQUEST

25.body: Means that the API key does not have permission to create data
25.title: ERR_CREATE_PERMISSION

26.body: Means that the API key does not have permission to write to existing data
26.title: ERR_WRITE_PERMISSION

27.body: Means that the API key does not have permission to delete data
27.title: ERR_DELETE_PERMISSION

28.body: Is returned when you are trying to create a resource that already exists. For example creating an entity with that name that is already being used by another entity
28.title: ERR_DUPLICATE

29.body: Is returned when the name parameter is missing from the request body
29.title: ERR_EMPTY_NAME

3.body: Every request made to the YOOT API must contain a valid API key in it's Authorization header. Head over to the next page to learn more about the different endpoints and how to use the API overall
3.title: API calls authentication

30.body: Is returned when a resource you are trying to access is not found. For example when trying to fetch data from an entity that does not exist
30.title: ERR_RESOURCE_NOT_FOUND

31.body:
Is returned when your request body contains data types that does not match the schema of an entity. For example //...refer to example in Entities page form_data.append('price', 'one thousand') fetch( 'https://api.yootcms.xyz/entities', { headers:{ "Authorization": "API_KEY_HERE" }, method:"POST", body: form_data }
) This will cause a ERR_WRONG_FIELD_TYPE because the price field is of type Number and we can not cast one thousand into a number
31.title: ERR_WRONG_FIELD_TYPE

32.body:
Is returned when a field of type Image receives data that is not a file For example //...refer to example in Entities page form_data.append('image', 'Some image') fetch( 'https://api.yootcms.xyz/entities', { headers:{ "Authorization": "API_KEY_HERE" }, method:"POST", body: form_data }
) This will cause a ERR_EXPECTED_IMAGE because the image field is of type Image, thus we expect you to send a Blob in the form data.
32.title: ERR_EXPECTED_IMAGE

33.body: Is returned when something goes wrong while uploading your image(s). When facing this error, try again and contact support if the error persists
33.title: ERR_IMAGE_UPLOAD
